SIMPLE: shadow
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shadow
<hw>Shad"ow</hw> <pr>(sh⟦acr⟧d"⟦osl⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[Originally the same word as <ets>shade</ets>. ⟦root⟧162. See
<er>Shade</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Shade within defined limits;
obscurity or deprivation of light, apparent on a surface, and
representing the form of the body which intercepts the rays of light;
<as>as, the <ex>shadow</ex> of a man, of a tree, or of a tower</as>. See
the Note under <er>Shade</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 1.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Darkness; shade; obscurity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Night's sable <qex>shadows</qex> from the ocean rise.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A shaded place; shelter; protection;
security.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In secret <qex>shadow</qex> from the sunny ray,⟦br⟧
On a sweet bed of lilies softly laid.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A reflected image, as in a mirror or in water.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>That which follows or attends a person or thing like
a shadow; an inseparable companion; hence, an obsequious
follower.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sin and her <qex>shadow</qex> Death.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A spirit; a ghost; a shade; a phantom.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Hence, horrible <xex>shadow</xex>!⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>An imperfect and faint representation; adumbration;
indistinct image; dim bodying forth; hence, mystical representation;
type.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The law having a <qex>shadow</qex> of good things to come.</q>
<rj><qau>Heb. x. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Types] and <qex>shadows</qex> of that destined seed.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A small degree; a shade.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧No
variableness, neither <xex>shadow</xex> of turning.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>James
i. 17.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>An uninvited guest coming with one who is
invited.</def> <mark>[A Latinism]</mark> <rj><au>Nares.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I must not have my board pastered with <qex>shadows</qex>⟦br⟧
That under other men's protection break in⟦br⟧
Without invitement.</q> <rj><qau>Massinger.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Shadow of death</b></col>, <cd>darkness or gloom like
that caused by the presence or the impending of death.</cd> <rj><au>Ps.
xxiii. 4.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shadow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shadow
<hw>Shad"ow</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Shadowed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shadowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>shadowen</ets>, AS.
<ets>sceadwian</ets>. See <er>adow</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut off light from; to put in shade; to shade; to
throw a shadow upon; to overspead with obscurity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The warlike elf much wondered at this tree,⟦br⟧
So fair and great, that <qex>shadowed</qex> all the ground.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To conceal; to hide; to screen.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let every soldier hew him down a bough.⟦br⟧
And bear't before him; thereby shall we <qex>shadow</qex>⟦br⟧
The numbers of our host.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To protect; to shelter from danger; to
shroud.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Shadowing</qex> their right under your wings of war.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To mark with gradations of light or color; to
shade.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To represent faintly or imperfectly; to adumbrate;
hence, to represent typically.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Augustus is <qex>shadowed</qex> in the person of ⟦AE⟧neas.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To cloud; to darken; to cast a gloom over.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>shadowed</qex> livery of the burnished sun.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why sad?⟦br⟧
I must not see the face O love thus <qex>shadowed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To attend as closely as a shadow; to follow and
watch closely, especially in a secret or unobserved manner; <as>as, a
detective <ex>shadows</ex> a criminal</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shadowiness</ent>⟦br⟧
